                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d428">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War, 1939/166: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-06T15:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 6, 1939—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 6—10:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>514. I am reliably informed that in a recent interview between the Polish
                    Ambassador and Molotov<note n="32" xml:id="d428fn32">Vyacheslav M. Molotov,
                        Chairman of the Council of People’s Commissars of the Soviet Union.</note>
                    the latter expressed surprise that England and France had actually declared war
                    on Germany.</p>
                <p>I also understand that although the Polish Ambassador endeavored to obtain from
                    Molotov a clarification of the Soviet attitude towards the Polish-German
                    conflict Molotov was non-committal and evasive.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
